You can always do a wrapper function. The details will depend on what you want, but for example:

``` js
function myScale(x){
  if (x === 0){
    return 0;
  }else{
    return myRealScale(Math.abs(x))
  }
}
```

Alternatively, use clamping to force the value onto the domain:

``` js
> myScale = d3.scale.log().domain([1, 100])
> myScale(0)
NaN
> myScale.clamp(true)
> myScale(0)
0
```
